,"attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: apparently a nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>fraser(e)</i>, <i>fresere</i> ‘strawberry plant’. <i>Fresel</i> and <i>Frisel</i>, from Anglo-Norman French <i>fresel</i> ‘strawberry’, are early variants of the Fraser surname, the modern Gaelicized form of which is <b>Friseal</b>. See   Frizzell  . The crest on the Scottish family's coat of arms takes the form of a strawberry plant, but its antiquity is unknown. Claims of a habitational derivation, in particular from a place called la Frézelière in Anjou (France), are attractive but they lack verifiable evidence.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","History: There are two clans Fraser in Scotland, with common ancestry going back to Simon Fraser of Keith in East Lothian, who lived in the 12th century. One of these clans has its seat at Philorth Castle (subsequently re-named Cairnbulg) on the northeast coast of Scotland. Sir Alexander Fraser, 8th laird of Philorth (<i>c.</i> 1536–1623) converted the fishing village of Faithlie into the burgh of Fraserburgh in the 1590s. The other clan is Fraser of Lovat, associated mainly with the city of Inverness are. They are descended from Simon Fraser, a younger son, who lived in the early 14th century. In Gaelic, the head of Clan Fraser of Lovat is known as <i>Mac Shimi</i> ‘son of Simon’."],"variants":[{"name":"Frayser","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frasier","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frasure","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frazer","meanings":["Variant of   Fraser  , associated chiefly with northern Ireland."]},{"name":"Fraizer","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frashier","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Fraiser","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frizzell","meanings":["English and Irish: nickname from Old French <i>fresel</i>, <i>frisel</i> ‘lace, ribbon, braid, brooch, frill, ruff’, for someone with an ornate style of dress, or ‘object of little value’ (a diminutive of <i>frese</i>, of ancient Germanic origin).","Scottish: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fresel</i> ‘strawberry’, an alternative form of   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frazier","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Fraser  .","Americanized form of French <b>Frégeau</b> (see   Fregeau  )."]},{"name":"Frasher","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Fraser  .","Possibly an altered form of German <b>Fratzscher</b> (see   Frutchey  )."]}]},{"name":"Eda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Éanna ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Eda Fraser was born in 1147, in Humbie, East Lothian, Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Simon Fraser, was 22 and her mother, Margaret Caithness, was 22. She had at least 1 daughter with Hugh Lorens. She died in Scotland."},"et":{"1147–":"1147–Surnud","1147–Female":"1147–Surnud","1149–Male":"1149–Surnud","1140–1220":"1140–1220","1166–1187":"1166–1187","1125–1190":"1125–1190","1125–Female":"1125–Surnud","1190":"1190","before 1147":"enne 1147","1149":"1149","1147":"1147","1125":"1125","before 1165":"enne 1165","1166":"1166","1187":"1187","1220":"1220","1140":"1140","about 1166":"umbes 1166","Humbie, East Lothian, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Humbie, East Lothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Humbie, East Lothian, Scotland":"Humbie, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Kelso, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Kelso, Roxburghshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1147–":"1147–Kuollut","1147–Female":"1147–Kuollut","1149–Male":"1149–Kuollut","1140–1220":"1140–1220","1166–1187":"1166–1187","1125–1190":"1125–1190","1125–Female":"1125–Kuollut","1190":"1190","before 1147":"ennen vuotta 1147","114